Introduction

The following EDA stems from being a long-time fan of the NBA. From countless debates with people about the GOAT, I have thought long and hard about who is the greatest basketball player of all time.

Overview

This overarching question is somewhat subjective based on your individual meaning of âgreat.â Not only have I looked into a range of factors that contribute to being the greatest, but Iâve also gotten into heated arguments with friends about who the GOAT of basketball is. Instead of simply pointing to the number of championships a player has won, I wanted to look into the statistics of all games played by Lebron James, Michael Jordan, and Kobe Bryant to justify who the best player is at the core of the game. I understand that longevity of a playerâs career and injuries may influence the data, but I plan to account for any confounding variables based on my ball knowledge and further thorough research.

Personally, I have been one of the biggest Lebron James fans my whole life, but I plan to put biases aside to let the numbers decide who the greatest player of all time is. I understand that Lebron James, Michael Jordan, and Kobe Bryant have all culturally changed the game. However, I would like to simplify the argument for the greatest basketball player of all time by analyzing the raw statistics provided.

Data Source

The source of my data is a user on Kaggle.com, named Xavier. Their username is xvivancos, and they are a data science enthusiast that is also a Kaggle Grandmaster. Their roots are from Barcelona and Catalonia, Spain. The archive of interest is named Michael Jordan, Kobe Bryant and Lebron James stats. In the EDA, I utilize a singular dataset called allgames_stats to compare the statistics from every game played by Lebron James, Michael Jordan, and Kobe Bryant. Some of my data analysis is also derived from a dataset called totals_stats to organize the data in a more general way. The allgames_stats is a great dataset that bypasses the idea of player longevity (an argument used in Lebronâs favor) by focusing on the first fifteen years of each playerâs career. This way, performance at corresponding points in each playerâs career can by compared to address the central question.

Approaching the Central Question

My central question revolves around which of the three basketball players in the dataset is the greatest basketball player of all time. To approach this question, Iâve decided to evaluate it by who was the most valuable player the most times between the three individuals. The timeframe is restricted to the first fifteen seasons of each playerâs respective career. This limits out the longevity arguments for players that have had longer careers than others. Now, I understand that the Most Valuable Player (MVP) in the NBA is often based on a playerâs merit as well as team success. To assign the MVP to one of these three players in their first fifteen seasons, I have come up with my own metric for evaluation.

The MVP will be a much more statistically based award. This is because I will be using a variety of stats reflecting a playerâs true impact over every single minute played during a season. To measure offensive output, I am including points, assists, and rebounds. For defensive output, I am additionally using steals and blocks. The specific Score for each player in a given season will be calculated by:

Score = (Points + Assists + Rebounds + Steals + Blocks) / Minutes Played

I am adjusting Points scored by each player to account for point inflation/deflation during time periods in the NBA. This is done with a normalization of points scored by each player to total points averaged by each of their respective teams in a given year.

Once this score is calculated for each game played in a given season for a player, the average of all the scores in a season will be computed as a final reflection for comparison. The greatest final mean score, each season, will justify who shouldâve won the MVP. Then, I plan to add up MVPs for each player and deduce which player is the most valuable the most number of seasons.

Following the computation of each playerâs score in their first fifteen seasons, I am going to evaluate it against turnovers and NBA GameScore to see how the score metric correlates with a variable reflecting negative player performance and with the overall efficiency score assigned to each player for a given game. Furthermore, I plan to also evaluate it against win totals in both the regular season and post season to see how effective the metric is with win success. I believe that this analysis justifies the quality of my score metric and who the greatest NBA player of all time is.

Data Overview and Quality

The allgames_stats dataset is approximately 533 KB in size, and it is sufficiently complex for my analysis.

Analyzing the data

In the dataset, there are 29 total variables and 4,254 total observations. Moreover, there are 6 categorical variables as well as 23 numerical variables. In terms of missingness, there is an issue for home games vs.Â away games.

Issues in the data

In this dataset, home games are represented with NA values for the X variable. Also, some of the statistical percentages reflect NA values because zero attempts were made. This is often indicative of players missing a game due to injury or extenuating circumstanace. Another issue of missingness arises with the absence of GameScore values for Michael Jordan because it was a relatively new statistic during his early career. Sometimes, NA values would appear because some advanced statistics were not accounted for. Finally, an issue arises very rarely with the absence of a regular statistic like Steals. However, there is under a 0.260% rate of absence for values in similar variables.

Cleaning the data

First, the NA values that indicated home vs.Â away games were inconsequential for my data analysis, so I ignored them. For statistical percentages, I also ignored NA values present because my analysis of player performance and output ignored efficiency statistics like percentage of field goals made. Instead, I am accounting for the NA values indicative of missed games and missing statistical percentages by utilizing MP or total minutes played in each game. This overcomes the absence of some values by narrowing the analysis to when each player was actively on the court. In order to use minutes played in the calculation of my score metric, I made sure to conver the MP variable from difftime type to a numeric type for effective manipulation of the corresponding data. The absence of GameScore values and regular statistical observations led to the removal of these minimal observations to clean out rare irregularities in the dataset for analysis.

Explorations

Analyzing distributions of key variables

Reasoning

To begin, I analyzed the most representative statistics for player performance in terms of offensive output and defensive output. The variables chosen were Points, Assists, Rebounds, Steals, and Blocks. These numbers reflect how a player contributed to winning in any given game. Also, I analyzed minutes played, so I could use this variable along with the five previous variables to calculate a score representative of a playerâs performance whenever they were on the court.

Plots and analysis

The density plot for points revealed the probability of scoring a certain number of points in any given game for an indicated player. According to this graph, Michael Jordan had the greatest center of distribution, meaning the addition of Points to the score metric would most benefit Jordan.

The density plot for assists revealed the probability of recording a certain number of assists in any given game for an indicated player. According to this graph, Lebron James had the greatest center of distribution, meaning the addition of Assists to the score metric would most benefit Lebron.

The density plot for rebounds revealed the probability of recording a certain number of assists in any given game for an indicated player. According to this graph, Lebron James had the greatest center of distribution, meaning the addition of Blocks to the score metric would most benefit Lebron. This makes sense because Lebron is the tallest, so he is more likely to come down with rebounds.

According to the table, Michael Jordan and Lebron James had a very similar average number of blocks, meaning the addition of Blocks to the score metric almost equally benefit Jordan and Lebron.

The histogram for minutes played revealed a unimodal, left-skewed distribution for all three players. The left skew can be attributed to early games in each playerâs career, where they each had to fight for minutes. However, the mode lies nearby the center of the distribution at approximately 40 minutes, indicating that all three players normally played around 40 minutes per game.

Reflection

Following the visualization of the important variables to be used in my Score metric, I noticed that the five variables seemed to benefit Lebron James and Michael Jordan somewhat equally. On the other hand, Kobe Bryant seemed to be lacking in each statistic. Because of each statistic values a unique but important part of the game, Points, Assists, Rebounds, Steals, and Blocks will be weighed equally on top of Minutes Played to reach a holistic score for the evaluation of MVP.

Conclusion

So far, I am proud of the data analysis performed, but there is definitely room for improvement. One area that is tough to get around is adjusting the scores to their respective time period accordingly. During various times in NBA history, the style of the game shifted in terms of strategy, defensive intensity, spacing, and scoring. To account for this in future analysis, I plan to adjust Point scored by each player to account for point inflation/deflation during different years. This could be done with a comparison between points scored and total points averaged by the respective team.
